The back - up drunk drivers will be ordered to install " Alcolock "
After three drunk driving violations , the Ministry of Interior would order the car driver to install a device that would prevent the vehicle from starting if the driver was drunk or did not blow into the structure .
The proposal was presented in June and is currently being addressed by the State 's Attorney 's Office , which says that the pilot project will last for a year .
Since the aim of the project is to restore the market , the car driver will also have to take part in a repeat course on transport education .
In addition to the Public Prosecutor ’s Office for Transport Safety , the Directorate - General for Transport ( DGT ) and the Institute for Autoboszsági Technology Foundation ( FITSA ) are also involved in the experiment .
According to statistics , 30 - 75 % of the drivers arrested repeatedly for driving drunks are back in the car .
Alcolock would prevent this , since the system connected to the vehicle determines the alcohol level of the air in the air . If it is larger than the permissible , or if the driver did not blow into the device at all , the system will not allow the car to start .
The cost of the instrument of more than € 1000 would be borne by the offender .
A study conducted in the USA in 2007 proved that vehicles equipped with such instruments could reduce the number of violations by up to 65 % in the first year after installation .
In Spain , it is estimated that 115 people could be saved every year by this rule .
The measure focuses on infringements for two reasons : on the one hand , it is easier to prevent them from becoming a crime ,
On the other hand , it is easier to introduce it , since the implementation of the legal reform takes place in the usual medier , while the necessary criminal reform requires a basic amendment to the law .
The instrument is not yet available in any commercial form on the Spanish market , although it has already been installed in experimental mode in some industrial and public service vehicles .
The Assembly votes tomorrow on the initiative of the Spanish Socialist Workers ' Party which calls for the installation of the system in school buses .
