Blood is safe again
President Francine Décary had a good reason to celebrate because Héma - Québec has become one of the safest and most effective blood donors in the world .
And most importantly , he managed to regain the trust of people , which was severely shaken by the blood - related disadvantage of the 1980s and 1990s .
As is known , the national blood reserve treated by the Canadian Red Cross blood supply service was infected with the acquired immune deficiency syndrome ( HIV ) and hepatitis C viruses in the 1980s .
Following the drama and general depression , the government of Canada launched an official investigation under Judge Horace Krever in February 1994 , which was designed to shed light on the circumstances that led to the tragedy and to propose proposals to avoid similar cases in the future .
While Judge Krever submitted a delayed report , some provinces set up their own committees to design a new blood treatment system for Canada .
In Québec , the Gélineau Committee was responsible for this task .
Following the Gélineau and Krever reports , two blood supply services were created in Canada : one is the Quebec Service Héma - Québec , and the other is the Canadian Blood Supply Company responsible for all other provinces and two territories .
" When the Héma - Québec began its activity in 1998 , only 38 % of people had confidence in Quebec 's blood supply system " , Dr. Décary remembers .
The situation was desperate .
" In the following years , however , we managed to regain the trust of people as a result of improving the safety of blood products and our work in the field . " Décary proudly stated that almost 94 % of the Québec population had considered the Héma - Québec reliable in early 2008 .
But Dr. Décary does not forget that " trust is a very fragile thing " .
Since its foundation on 28 September 1998 , the Héma - Québec has applied the principle of caution .
During this period , many cases in Europe were discovered when the new variations of the Creutzfeldt - Jakob disease have infected people , the doctor says , who has been controlling the company since its foundation in 1998 .
" We had no idea if this disease was spreading through blood .
Therefore , we relied on one of the most important recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports . In this case , if we are uncertain and there is a risk of developing a serious disease , we must apply precluding measures . In this case , Creutzfeldt - Jakob was a disease that causes brain lesions , thus inevitably leads to death .
Therefore , in April 1999 , we did not take blood from people who spent more than a month in the UK since 1980 .
And a few years ago , it was undoubtedly determined that the disease spreads through blood .
This case convinced us that we had a reason to apply the principle of caution . "
In 1999 , a technique appeared on the market that allows for a much more sensitive diagnosis of the HIV virus . This nucleic acid test ( NNAT ) , which can directly detect the virus in the blood of blood transmitters , rather than antibodies that are created against the virus , for which the tests used earlier were built .
With the help of the NAT test , we could shorten the window period , which lasts from infection until we can show the virus in the blood using our technical tools , explains the specialist .
This period was reduced to less than a week .
This has led to a significant reduction in the risk of blood donors infecting the blood vessel beyond their knowledge , and that this can not be detected .
These developments have greatly reduced the risk of AIDS spread through blood transfusion .
Nowadays , the risk of getting infected with HIV is 12 million to one .
" In other words , this means we should allocate 12 million blood products until someone gets infected with HIV .
Since theéma - Québec distributes 400 - 500 thousand blood products every year , more than 24 years should pass to a case like this and someone is infected with HIV virus through a blood treatment .
I think that anyone can accept or prescribe blood transfusions to restore health nowadays , says the chief leader of the Héma - Québec .
" The challenge of the next decade will be to maintain the reliability of our products .
We never know what kind of new pathogen is going to enter the system .
It was only last year that the Chikungunya virus appeared on Réunion , which , like the West Nile virus , enters the blood with insect bites .
Therefore , we must constantly be alert , ” said Dr. Décary , and stressed that aside from the emergency reserves , the Héma - Québec must provide sufficient permanent reserves .
" The needs of the population are increasing by ageing .
Since anticancer treatments have become more aggressive , patients often need to replace red blood cells or platelets .
The ageing of the population also affects the blood donors , as the number of people in the network that are capable of blood is only 3 % of the population of Quebec .
However , all healthy persons , at least 18 years old , can give blood to the person who fulfills the conditions of suitability every 56 days , that is , six times a year .
On average , 14 % of applicants do not accept blood because they are infected with AIDS or malaria , and those who have been in a country where malaria is destroyed are not entitled to blood for a year .
" With this 3 percent , we have enough reserves to meet the needs of hospitals .
It 's very rare that we run out of supplies .
However , we need to increase the number of blood donors to the extent that the existing ones age , because they can no longer give blood after a while .
But it 's very hard to convince people to give blood , but it 's even harder to keep them and make them become regular blood taxes .
In this world of rush today , one has barely got an hour to go to give blood " , pityed by Francine Décary .
The Héma - Québec , an annual budget of $ 297 million , not only provides blood products , but also human tissues , such as bone transplants , heart valves , eyeball tissues and skin tissue , which is used almost exclusively for severely burned individuals .
These tissues are analyzed , converted and frozen , then placed at theéma - Québec , which also manages the only public stem cell bank in Quebec .
Only blood from the umbilical cord , which was treated as medical waste , can be extracted from blood that is rich in stem cells , thus also allows the treatment of serious diseases ( such as leukemia ) .
" A few weeks ago , we celebrated the thousands of umbilical blood samples in our bank , and we plan to take over a thousand new samples every year .
At the beginning of next year we will probably start offering these for organ transplants , ” said Dr. Décary , who says the umbilical blood - extraction program is very popular today .
" Many mothers are sad because they do n't have the opportunity " - indeed , it is , because theéma - Québec has no way of making this complex and costly program available in every hospital in Quebec .
