The pictures taken by director Giuseppe Tornatore effectively showcase everything that goes on in the Italian cities , but also in rural regions .
The suppression of cinemas - the appearance of large , multi -term cinemas in the suburbs , and as a consequence , the failure of one - of - a - kinders in the city centre - seems inevitable and irreversible , but at the same time bears all the characteristics of a real cultural crime .
When places with historical and memory disappear , " it 's like a friend leaving , a friend with whom we shared our journey and many experiences , " says Cinema Paradiso director . The film , which was an Oscar award twenty years ago , and the grand prize of the Cannes festival , tells Tornator 's story of a small - town cinema 's másodpercarist story , the yearning , after a movie experience that may have been lost forever .
The largest association of operators , the data provided by Anec , has been clear : 316 traditional film theatres have closed in the last five years . The biggest losses could be recorded in films in large cities : 10 film theatres closed in Florence , 9 in Milan , Naples , Bologna and Rome , 6 in Turin , and 5 in Palermo .
Among the most affected regions , Emilia - Romagna is at the forefront , which lost 82 single -term cinema , followed by Tuscany ( 44 ) and Lombardy ( 41 ) .
And that the number of newly opened multi -term cinemas in these three regions of Italy is the highest in the past five years : the number of rooms in Lombardy has risen by 195 , 81 in Tuscany and the same in Emilia - Romagna .
